Mr Kiraitu said his administration is in the process of putting up a Sh1.6 billion cancer centre that will offer both diagnosis and treatment services.
Currently, the hospital has a bed capacity of 338 against an average inpatient occupancy of 450.
The hospital collects more than Sh413.5 million annually and intends to increase the collection by Sh100 million in five years.
Among the services targeted for boosting revenue include establishment of hearse services, a private inpatient wing and a doctors’ plaza, among others. The hospital also intends to adopt the use of clean energy to cut costs.

